Job Description:
Purpose of Job:

The Pharmaceutical Production Director will be involved with the planning, coordination and control of manufacturing processes. 

He will ensure that goods and services are produced efficiently and that the correct amount is produced at the right cost and level of quality.

Primary Responsibilities:

The Pharmaceutical Production Director will be responsible for both human and material resources. The job will be involved in the pre-production (planning) stage as well as the production (control and supervision) stage. And involved with product design and purchasing, with assistant from Planners, controllers, production engineers and production supervisors. And will also work closely with other functions, such as marketing, sales and finance (mainly during financial review quarterly).

Activities and tasks:

- Overseeing the production process, drawing up a production schedule;
- Analyze, reduce costs and ensuring that the production is cost effective; making sure that products are produced on time and are of good quality;
- Working out the human and material resources needed; drafting a timescale for the job;
- Estimating costs and setting the quality standards; Develop production schedules and duty assignments.
- Ensure compliance with workplace safety programs; monitoring the production processes and adjusting schedules as needed;
- Being responsible for the selection and maintenance of equipment; monitoring product standards and implementing quality-control programmes; Correct problems on production line.
- Liaising among different departments, e.g. suppliers, managers; working with managers to implement the company's policies and goals; ensuring that health and safety guidelines are followed;
- Hire and train workers; supervising and motivating a team of workers; reviewing worker performance;
- Identifying training needs and implement training programs; Implement and oversee quality control programs.
- Coordinate with different departments in the manufacturing plant.
- Work with the financial departments to come up with a budget and spending plan.
- Manage communication lines with managers, suppliers, and procurement departments.
- Cross-train worker teams for maximum production flexibility.

